actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed report and the image link.

The `Pixels` property is a convenience wrapper that intentionally throws when decoding fails. To detect a bad image without exception handling, use the `GetPixels` overload that returns `SKCodecResult` directly:

```csharp
using var codec = SKCodec.Create(filename);
if (codec == null) {
    // file not found or format not supported
    return;
}

var result = codec.GetPixels(out byte[] pixels);
if (result == SKCodecResult.Success || result == SKCodecResult.IncompleteInput) {
    // pixels contains the decoded image data
} else {
    // result is SKCodecResult.InvalidInput for a corrupt/truncated image
    Console.WriteLine($"Could not decode image: {result}");
}
```

`SKCodecResult.InvalidInput` is returned when Skia's JPEG decoder encounters a corrupt or structurally invalid image — the same case you linked to in the upstream Skia codec. The `GetPixels` overload lets you inspect this result code without needing a try/catch.
